A lipico or lipiko (plural : mapico or mapiko) is a mask or helmet of the Makonde of Mozambique. 
Lipico mask from Mozambique 
Mapico masks are worn for ceremonial dances during the rites of passage of circumcised boys called mapico dances.[1][2] These masks are carved by master craftsmen,[3] they are made of soft wood and often feature human hair. 
They represent faces of men or women with labrets or scarifications.[4] 
