Leigh Ashton (born 11 April 1956 in Manchester, England) is a South African singer, songwriter, pianist, performer and recording artist from Johannesburg, South Africa. 
Ashton was born in Manchester, England, on 11 April 1956 and moved to South Africa at the age of three. 
Ashton was signed to David Gresham Productions as a singer songwriter at 19. 
His first single "Love Me" was released in November 1975. 
Ashton worked with some of the best musicians in the country at the time including Trevor Rabin, Julian Laxton and Allan Goldswain.[1] The following year he performed at the very successful "Colosseum Mighty Music Machine" alongside local household names such as Bobby Angel, Bruce Millar, Richard Loring and Sonya Herholdt[2] but he still had yet to achieve his own recognition. In 1977 "Tanya", one of his own songs, reached no 12 on the official SA charts based on sales – competing with ABBA and Leo Sayer.[3] "Tanya" was released on Pye Records later that year in England and Europe.[4] A series of newspaper articles, TV videos, pin up photos and radio interviews followed and he released his third single "Day after Day" another self penned song.[5] 
Cecil Kenneth Baker (1921 – November 1996[1]) was a South African artist.[2] 
Baker was born at Harfield Road, Claremont, Cape Town, South Africa,[3] which was, at the time of his birth, a predominantly working class[4] suburb. 
