A civil and political activist, Mohamud was previously a university professor and dean.[2] 
Hassan frequented primary and secondary schools in his hometown.[9] He later moved to Somalia's capital Mogadishu in 1978, where he studied for three years at the local Somali National University. 
In 1981, he earned an undergraduate diploma in technology from the institution.[2][3] 
In 1986, Hassan journeyed to India and began attending Bhopal University (now Barkatullah University). 
There, he completed a master's degree in technical education in 1988.[1] Hassan is also a graduate of Eastern Mennonite University's Summer Peacebuilding Institute based in Harrisonburg, Virginia. In 2001, he completed three of the SPI's intensive courses, studying mediation, trauma healing, and designing learner-centered trainings.[10] 
