Fatimata Gandigui Mariko, better known as Fati Mariko (born 1964), is a Nigerien singer. 
Mariko received her education in Niamey and Bougouni and developed her typing skills before becoming a musician. 
Her hit song "Djana-Djana", produced with the group Marhaba and released in 1986, brought her her first fame. 
Mariko has sustained her career as a hit singer for over three decades, sometimes partnering with male stars and hip-hop groups in her productions. 
Her music is mainly derived from Zarma-Songhay ritual and folk music.[1] She sings in French and in various native languages of Niger, including Hausa, Djerma, and Fula.[2] Her albums include Issa Haro and Inch Allah.[3] 
