Emmanuel N'Djoké "Manu" Dibango (12 December 1933 – 24 March 2020)[2] was a Cameroonian musician and songwriter who played saxophone and vibraphone. 
He developed a musical style fusing jazz, funk, and traditional Cameroonian music. 
His father was a member of the Yabassi ethnic group, while his mother was a Duala. 
He was best known for his 1972 single "Soul Makossa". 
He died from COVID-19 on 24 March 2020.[3][4] 
